To create a cron job in Golang without using an external library, you can use the built-in functionalities of the `time` package along with a goroutine. Here's an example of how you can achieve this:

```go
package main

import (
	"fmt"
	"time"
)

func main() {
	// Create a goroutine to run the cron job
	go func() {
		for {
			// Execute the cron job logic here
			fmt.Println("Cron job executed at:", time.Now().Format("2006-01-02 15:04:05"))

			// Pause the goroutine for the desired interval (e.g., every 5 seconds)
			time.Sleep(5 * time.Second)
		}
	}()

	// Keep the main goroutine running indefinitely
	// You can add other application logic here if needed
	select {}
}
```

In this example, the `main` function creates a goroutine using an anonymous function `func() { ... }`. The function contains the logic for your cron job. In this case, it simply prints a message with the current timestamp.

The goroutine then pauses for the desired interval (in this case, 5 seconds) using `time.Sleep()`. After the pause, the cron job logic will execute again.

To keep the main goroutine running indefinitely and prevent the program from exiting, we use `select {}`.

You can modify the cron job logic and the sleep duration to fit your specific requirements. Remember to handle any potential errors or add necessary error-checking code in your cron job implementation.

Yes, you can activate a cron job at a specific time (e.g., 12 AM) and make it run once each day. Here's an updated version of the previous code to achieve this:

```go
